  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "When do I declare a Brisbane property sale on my tax return?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "You declare the sale in the financial year that the contract is signed, not the year of settlement. This is the contract date rule under section 104-10 of the Income Tax Assessment Act. If you sign a contract on 28 June 2026 with settlement on 12 August 2026, the capital gains tax event occurs in the 2025 to 2026 financial year and the sale belongs on that year's tax return, even though the money does not change hands until the following year. This catches many Brisbane sellers off guard, especially around 30 June. If the property is your main residence and the full exemption applies, you do not need to declare it. For investment properties, the gain or loss must be declared in the contract-date financial year."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What needs to go on a tax return in the year I sell a Brisbane investment property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Four things change on the return in the year of sale. First, partial-year rental income and deductions: you declare rent received up to settlement date plus apportioned interest, rates, insurance, body corporate, agent fees, and other holding costs for the period the property was rented. Second, the capital gain or loss calculation: cost base less capital proceeds, with the 50 percent discount if you held the property over twelve months as an individual. Third, depreciation recapture and balancing adjustments on any plant and equipment that was being claimed. Fourth, the ATO clearance certificate if the property sold for $750,000 or more, which prevents 12.5 percent foreign resident withholding being applied to your proceeds. Each of these is its own label on the return and needs supporting records."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I reduce the tax bill in the year I sell a Brisbane property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, in several ways, and the lead time matters. Carry-forward concessional super contributions of up to five years of unused cap can be made in the same financial year as the gain, which can shelter a significant portion of a large CGT event for individuals under 75 who meet the work test exemption. Realising capital losses from underperforming shares or other CGT assets in the same financial year can offset the gain. Prepaying deductible expenses such as a final year of interest on a remaining investment loan or income protection premiums can pull deductions into the high-income year. For sellers over 55, the Downsizer Contribution allows up to $300,000 of sale proceeds into super outside the contribution caps if eligibility rules are met. Each of these needs to be set up before 30 June of the contract-date financial year, not after."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does the ATO automatically know I sold my Brisbane property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Queensland's Office of State Revenue, the land titles registry, and the ATO share property transaction data. The sale will appear in the ATO's pre-fill data the year after the contract is signed, and in many cases the ATO will issue a reminder or pre-populate the CGT label on your return. If you omit the sale or under-report the gain, the ATO will detect the discrepancy through data matching. The practical implication is that you cannot quietly leave a sale off the return, and the records you keep at the time of the transaction need to support the position you take on the return, particularly for main residence exemption claims and cost base calculations."
      }
    }
  ]
};
